The place had great service and the cook did a great job with the products he was given. However- the quality of the product wasn't very good at all and the prices reflect that. It has a small town, homey feel and it looks as though a lot of regulars enjoy hanging out there. The ketchup in the bottle had been sitting a while- very fermented.< /Review>

<Text>Excellent food, super friendly staff, but very slow. Also serving people out of turn.

After 30 minutes, and everyone else getting their food, more locals arrived and those arriving 30 minutes after us got their food.

<name>Uriel Rodriguez<//name><Pics>None<//Pics><user_id>109479641890832523351< /user_id>< Review>
One of the only places where you can find Birria de Chivo. The birria has very little fat so the majority of what you're given is meat. The toppings go well with it, and the chile is spicy so it adds a ton of flavor. The tortillas that come with the plate ARE handmade and very soft. They have an authentic flavor as well. The tacos are very yummy and they have a ton of flavor. It comes with some of the birria broth so you can dip the tacos. The nachos I ordered were very crunchy and had a good amount of asada. Very delicious for something new, but with all the flavor of Sinaloa<//Review>

< review>
2 spicy Tonkatsu ramens, one with chicken and one with pork belly. This place has the best ramen I've had in a restaurant. Every restaurant I've been to had bland ramen, but sake sushi hits those taste buds.
I've had the shuyo and miso ramen as well, but It has been a while.
The pork belly is tender, with a bit of fat on it; it has a really good flavor to it. The chicken has no flavor but its still good with the broth. The noodles are PERFECT, not aw mushy, they are a perfect al dente. Overall this place always hits the spot, even on a hot day lol.
If you like ramen and find it hard to find a really good ramen place, THIS place can definitely fill the craving.</review>

< Review>
They missed a few small dirt and soap spots. Auto City is pricey at $42 for the basic car wash, plus additional tip. I remember when this place charged less than $20. I hope that the employees have had their salaries doubled as a result of these steep price increases and that the profits are not going entirely to the owner of this car wash.

Like a number of businesses in San Francisco, the few remaining full service car wash stations maintain a monopoly on this service. So it appears they can charge whatever they wish.

Anyone know of a more reasonably priced full service car wash in or near San Francisco? If not, I suppose I'll just have my car washed less often.<//Review>

< Review>
We ordered two Croque Madame sandwiches, French Onion soup and two lattes. Both sandwiches and soup were really good. I was very impressed their commitment to quality. The barista who made our coffee, told us that one of the espresso shots came out wrong and she needs to remake it. Many coffee shops would still serve it as is. All staff members were very friendly and polite. Coffee shop has a cozy and clean decor. Would highly recommend.</Review>

< UserId.>
112194635338851283539< /UserId.>
<user_name>John Wadleigh< /user_name>< Time>
1574017001483< /Time>
< rating>
5<//rating>
< Review>
Worth it! Ok, let me start by saying that I was born and raised in Coronado and Clayton's has been a part of Coronado for a long time. With so many failed restaurants in Coronado lately I was nervous to visit Clayton's new bakery and bistro. I honestly just didn't want to risk it. I had been to various other new places in Coronado and they simply were terrible. This place however... well, it shocked me! I am a pretty serious critic when it comes to restaurants - I travel all over the world and have experienced all types. So to tell you that this place is "worth it", well I am over the moon! Finally a restaurant that got it right. I ordered the french onion soup because I just couldn't believe they could pull it off right. Well they nailed it!! It was sooo delicious! I paired it with a glass of red wine and then finished it all off with one of their grilled cheese sandwiches, which was simple in concept but delivered spectacularly with homemade chips. Thank you Clayton's for bringing something great to this town finally. Cheers!<//Review>

<name>Sona Sood<//name><date>1565803598469</date><rating>5<//rating><Text>I don't know where to start with this restaurant. Everything about them is exquisite. I held a farewell wedding breakfast there on Sunday, and my guests are still raving about the food, the presentation, and the kindness of the servers. We were a large group, and we were seated on the front patio (which is beautiful). It has an expansive feel with flowers lining the edges.

I could not have asked for anything else. The food was timed perfectly, tasted fresh and delicious, the tables looked gorgeous with the chinaware and the food displays, and the staff was so relaxed and easy going. They augmented the celebration with their beautiful presence.

The restaurant also offers gluten-free options which is fantastic. My guests had different dietary requirements/requests, and the restaurant was able to handle all of them with ease.

Finally, the owners. I had a chance to meet Chelsea who seemed very kind, and I worked with Mary. From the moment I began texting Mary to prepare for this event, I started growing excited about holding the event here. She was enthusiastic, open to ideas, and willing to compromise on a request I made. She is an absolute delight. Additionally, when I was leaving I mentioned that I would prefer food doesn't get wasted. A perfect breakfast was concluded with her telling me that they donate the food to the SEALs, and they also have a relationship with shelters over the bridge where they can share food.

The passion, heart, love, and beauty of this restaurant is rare. Absolute gem in Coronado. I cannot wait to go back.< /Text>< Pictures>

<Rating>2<//Rating>< Review>
If you like huge plates of mediocre seafood (at best) this is the place for you. Our server was very competent but I only go because my elderly sister likes the huge plates of stuff. Certainly not for the food. The pasta was overcooked. The two types of lobster were overcooked. The shrimp were tasteless. The biscuits could have used a few extra minutes in the oven but the flavor was what I expected. The mashed potatoes had been around a while. The hostess was chatting away with some other workers and couldn't have missed me waiting at her stand for a long awaited table. Spend your hard-earned somewhere else if you want seafood. There are so many better places.< /Review>

<Text>I like red lobster but you have to understand why your coming here. All the food we have had here is cooked very well.  Service can be hit or miss. Our challenge has always been around crab legs.

My wife loves crab legs. They are cooked well and taste good but one thing or another always happens. We either don't get the right tools to crack them open, they forget to cut them for easier access to the meat, or they are cold.

I have always gotten, lobster in some form or another had it has been great. Fish is cooked well and taste great.

Their biscuits always has to much salt. Some people like it, we don't.

You pay less at red lobster but you need to order to their strong suits and keep expectations in check.

They are in a different class than Kings Fish, and Taps is in an even different class. I know your spending $35 for a meal, but at taps that meal would be $70 and up, but it would be worth every bit it.

If I just want some lobster, then I go to Red Lobster.  If I want a someone to cater to my every need, be in a much more formal setting, top of the line quality, then I got to Taps, but I also pay for it.

My wife will now knows not to order crab legs.

We will be back.< /Text><name>John D<//name>< Response>

<rating>3</rating>< Text>
I like Red Lobster for its reasonably priced seafood. We decided to go out on a Thursday night, so we wouldn't have to deal with the crowds. Although I had placed us on the "Wait List", there was no wait on our arrival. We were seated quickly and our waitress was there in minutes. All good. Food and drinks were provided in a timely manner. Also good. Our problem was in receiving seconds on the Endless Shrimp. We waited 20 minutes for each new serving. That's a long time to wait between servings. Upon complaint, we were told they were short on cooks. Hmmmm... that shouldn't be our problem, but if this had been mentioned first, then we could have ordered seconds accordingly. All-in-all, I think it will be awhile before we return.</Text>

<user>107958339684988462829< /user><Name>Harrieth Robinson<//Name><Time>1550903482052< /Time><Rating>3< /Rating>< Review>
Visited this establishment for a private intimate dinner with my husband. I informed the waiter that we were celebrating his birthday. So I looked forward to the customary dessert and birthday song after dinner.
We ordered the Seaside trio with a Cesar salad. I noticed that the price has gone up and portion size went down. The food taste well but the salad was lacking sufficient dressing.
Our waitor seemed to be in a hurry and was quite forgetful. To my dismay he tottaly forgot about the fact we were celebrating a birthday. Needless to say no ice cream or song.
He left the bill on the table and disappeared. Now I remember why I had stop coming to this Red Lobster in Lakewood. I much prefer the one in Torrance.<//Review>

<user>102145302717935133107</user>< username>
Traviett Ford< /username>
<Date>1546707557380<//Date>< rate>

< Text>
The hubs and I went to celebrate our wedding anniversary, and I think we simply chose the wrong time of day to show up. It was just before 4:30pm, and, at least, five staff members showed up behind us. There was no one out front, so we waited, and waited, as crew member after crew member walked this way and that. One person eventually said someone would be with us, and more time passed. Our waitress was very nice. She seemed quite distracted, however. Our section wasn't very packed, but I suppose it was busy enough. We waited quite some time for our waters, and the biscuits. After taking our order, the food arrived rather quickly. My mashed potatoes were cold. It was odd, because the rest of my food was hot. Perhaps they were placed on the plate first, before the rest of the food was cooked? We needed tartar sauce, ketchup, and cocktail sauce. When it finally arrived, there wasn't enough for each plate. We were asked if we wanted more biscuits. We did, but they never came. Perhaps she didn't here our, "Yes" response? Also, there was an upcharge on one of the drinks, when we specifically asked if there was a deviation from the listed price. The hot food was delicious. The cold mashed potatoes was very disappointing. The lack of attention to the specific requested condiments and additional biscuits, was very disappointing, as well. We did receive a refill on our water, and after specifying again, we received the correct number of condiments and lids for our leftovers. By the time we left, it was busy. Every table in our section was filled, and there was a line out front. I have mixed feelings about this visit, as it seems things got better by the end, when it was actually busy. We've received better service from Denny's, on a Saturday morning, and they stay packed!  Red Lobster earned two stars. I hope they can redeem themselves, IF I ever decide to go back. #disappointed<//Text>

First restaurant my father and I went to after his lengthy hospitalization (it's like 300 feet from Kaiser Permanente). The food was okay, however the service was a little slow that night.
